It may thus without any great impropriety of language be employed, as here, to denote the selection of a single instance to exhibit the working of a rulo. In this sense proponere is used by Boethius Introductio ad Sylloyismos Ooteyorioos. The usa of the corresponding word converso, as employed by didi-ich, is sanctioned by Boethius ibid; and may thus be regarded os more accurate historically, as well as more oppro- priate in itself. Many logicians however employ it in an opposite sense. Thus the Oxford predecessore of Aldrich‚ Grakanthorpe, Sanderson‚ and walis, all use converso for the proposition given to be convertod, convertens for that inferred from it.
